{"query": "What are the documented outcomes and challenges of rearing bumblebees in captivity for reintroduction?", "summary": "From 22 trials across 13 countries, captive rearing of bumblebee colonies has been attempted using various methods including confining mated queens alone or with different groups. Three trials specifically focused on declining North American species, with some success in rearing yellow-banded bumblebees B. terricola and red-belted bumblebees B. rufocinctus, but consistent failure in rearing yellow bumblebees B. fervidus, rusty-patched bumblebees, and American bumblebees B. pensylvanicus due to larvae dying before reaching adulthood.

Seven replicated trials monitored laboratory-reared colonies released to the wild, with four trials tracking colonies until new queen production or queen death. Two UK trials showed very low or zero queen production, while two trials achieved good queen numbers. Variable outcomes were observed regarding social parasitism by cuckoo bees Bombus [Psithyrus] spp., with two trials reporting high parasitism rates (25-66% and 79%), while five trials reported no social parasites.

Diet quality significantly impacts reproductive success - colonies fed freshly frozen pollen produced larger, longer-surviving queens than those fed dried, frozen pollen, and higher protein pollen types increased worker offspring production. Artificial light regimes of 8 hours light and 16 hours darkness reduced egg-laying time compared to constant darkness. Hibernation at 4-5°C for 45 days enhanced egg-laying and colony formation but resulted in smaller colonies, with queens needing to weigh over 0.6 g and be hibernated for four months or less for good survival rates. However, one four-year study found B. terrestris queens gradually decreased in weight during artificial rearing.", "action_ids": ["50", "52"]}

