{
  "query": "What is the extent of evidence on the success of translocating bees or augmenting small populations to improve genetic diversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence on bee translocation and genetic augmentation is limited. Only one trial in Brazil demonstrated that genetic diversity can be maintained in small isolated populations of stingless bees (Melipona scutellaris) by regularly introducing inseminated queens. For translocation specifically, one replicated trial in India showed that translocating carpenter bees (Xylocopa fenestrata) in immature stages can establish a population at a new site, but when adult bees are translocated, only a very small proportion remain at the new site. No evidence was found for the effects of ensuring genetic variation to increase translocation success in bees specifically, although this has been studied in other taxa. The systematic searches found no studies that directly evaluated the effects of introducing mated females to increase genetic diversity in butterflies and moths, indicating a significant gap in the evidence base for genetic augmentation across pollinator groups.",
