{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the effectiveness of different sown floral mixes on agricultural land for wild bees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from European studies shows that sown floral mixes on agricultural land can significantly enhance wild bee populations, particularly bumblebees. Agricultural nectar and pollen mixes containing perennial leguminous plants attract significantly more foraging bumblebees than naturally regenerated, grassy or cropped field margins (action 18). However, these mixes degrade in their value over time and need to be re-sown every few years. Native wildflower mixes also support higher abundance and species richness of foraging bumblebees compared to cropped edges, grassy margins or naturally regenerated areas (action 19), with perennial leguminous herbs being particularly important forage sources for long-tongued bumblebee species. Planting dedicated floral resources including phacelia has shown substantial foraging by wild bees, with trials recording 8-35 bee species visiting planted patches (action 17). Comparisons between mix types show that agricultural forage plant mixtures (including legumes) attract greater numbers of bumblebees than perennial wildflower mixes, at least in the first year after establishment. The evidence indicates that both agricultural and native wildflower mixes are effective, with agricultural mixes showing stronger initial attraction but requiring more frequent re-sowing to maintain effectiveness.",
