{
  "query": "What factors are known to influence the occupancy and productivity of artificial nest sites provided for solitary bees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Studies from Europe, North and South America and Asia show that many solitary bee species readily occupy artificial nest sites including cut hollow stems or tubes and blocks of wood drilled with holes. Reed stem and wooden grooved-board nest boxes demonstrate higher productivity than plastic-lined holes or plastic/paper tubes which experience increased parasitism and mould issues. Cardboard straws in drilled wooden holes produce more nests than grooved wooden boards stacked together. Nest box placement is critical - solitary bees have foraging ranges of 150-600 m so boxes must be within this distance of forage resources. Mortality rates vary significantly across studies, ranging from 2% brood cell attack in Indonesian plantations to 56% overall mortality for carpenter bees in India. Introduced species may competitively occupy nest boxes over native bees, and soil-filled nest boxes for mining bees have proven unsuccessful. Repeated nest box provision over multiple years can double the number of occupied nests.",
